Predictive Policing: Narcotics in Chicago City

Xiaoyi Wu

10/28/2021

Introduction

Selection bias is a distortion in a measure of association (such as a risk ratio) due to a sample selection that does not accurately reflect the true distribution of target population. In the crime prediction model, selection bias results from officers and local residents preconcieved beliefs. For example, policeman may strengthen patrolling in certain neighborhoods based on their subjective judgement, and residents living in some place may be indifferent to crimes and might not choose to report it. Thus, the selection bias may cause social inefficiency without proper resource allocation as well as social equity issues.

In light of this, this project predicted the occurrence of Narcotics in Chicago City and explored the impact of selection bias on geospatial risk models in different contexts.

Firstly, socio-economic data were wrangled from ACS tracts and exposure to a series of geospatial risk factors like vacant buildings, potholes, abandoned vehicles based on Broken Window Theory was used to do feature engineering. Secondly, model performance between spatial regression model and traditional Kernel Density was compared to analyze accuracy and generalizability. Finally, model performance was validated based on narcotics data in 2018.

### 2 Fishnet Map Since crime occurrence is a phenomenon related to neighbor effects, this study integrated the spatial factor into models by creating a fishnet with 500ft by 500ft grid cells and aggravated the crime count on grid cell level.

fishnet <- 
  st_make_grid(chicagoBoundary,
               cellsize = 500, 
               square = TRUE) %>%
  .[chicagoBoundary] %>%            # <- MDH Added
  st_sf() %>%
  mutate(uniqueID = rownames(.))

### Aggregate points to the fishnet
## add a value of 1 to each crime, sum them with aggregate
crime_net <- 
  dplyr::select(nar) %>% 
  mutate(countNar = 1) %>% 
  aggregate(., fishnet, sum) %>%
  mutate(countNar = replace_na(countNar, 0),
         uniqueID = rownames(.),
         cvID = sample(round(nrow(fishnet) / 100), 
                       size=nrow(fishnet), replace = TRUE))
                       
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = crime_net, aes(fill = countNar), color = NA) +
  scale_fill_viridis() +
  labs(title = "Narcotic count for the fishnet",
       subtitle="Chicago, 2017") +
  mapTheme()

3 Map of Risk Factors in Fishnet

According to the broken Windows Theory, any visible signs of crime and civil disorder, such as broken windows (hence, the name of the theory) vandalism create an urban environment that promotes even more crime and disorder.

Thus, this study selected geospatial exposure to abandoned cars, abandoned, vacant buildings, graffiti, liquor retails, sanitation, garbage carts, pothole and rodent baiting to conduct feature engineering and aggravated them on grid cells.

The map below shows the clustering of abandoned buildings are located at south Chicago. Abandoned cars are mainly focused in north Chicago. Garbage carts and out street light are distributed across the city. Liquor retailers are concentrated in the north side. Graffiti are distributed along with corridors of the 90, 290 and 55 highways.

4 Local Morans I

The plots below shows that local Morans I of the dependent variable. According to it, relatively high values of Morans I was observed, indicating strong and statistically significant evidence of spatial clustering in narcotics in northwestern Chicago.

## important to drop the geometry from joining features

# loop point
loopPoint <-
  filter(neighborhoods, name == "Loop") %>%
  st_centroid()

vars_net$loopDistance =
  st_distance(st_centroid(vars_net),loopPoint) %>%
  as.numeric() 

  
final_net <-
  left_join(crime_net, st_drop_geometry(vars_net), by="uniqueID") 

final_net <-
  st_centroid(final_net) %>%
    st_join(dplyr::select(neighborhoods, name), by = "uniqueID") %>%
    st_join(dplyr::select(policeDistricts, District), by = "uniqueID") %>%
      st_drop_geometry() %>%
      left_join(dplyr::select(final_net, geometry, uniqueID)) %>%
      st_sf() %>%
  na.omit()

final_net.nb <- poly2nb(as_Spatial(final_net), queen=TRUE)
final_net.weights <- nb2listw(final_net.nb, style="W", zero.policy=TRUE)

## see local moran
local_morans <- localmoran(final_net$countNar, final_net.weights, zero.policy=TRUE) %>% 
  as.data.frame()

# join local Moran's I results to fishnet
final_net.localMorans <- 
  cbind(local_morans, as.data.frame(final_net)) %>% 
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(Drug_Count = countNar, 
                Local_Morans_I = Ii, 
                P_Value = `Pr(z != E(Ii))`) %>%
  mutate(Significant_Hotspots = ifelse(P_Value <= 0.001, 1, 0)) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -geometry)

vars<-unique(final_net.localMorans$Variable)
varList<-list()
for(i in vars){
  varList[[i]]<-
    ggplot()+
    geom_sf(data=filter(final_net.localMorans,Variable==i),
            aes(fill=Value),colour=NA)+
    scale_fill_viridis(name="")+
    labs(title=i)+
    mapTheme()+
    theme(legend.position="bottom")}
do.call(grid.arrange,c(varList,ncol=4,top="Local Morans I statistics, Narcotics"))

7 K-fold Cross Validation

reg.vars <- c("Abandoned_Buildings.nn", "Abandoned_Cars.nn","Graffiti.nn","Liquor_Retail.nn", "Street_Lights_Out.nn", "Sanitation.nn","loopDistance","pothole.nn","garbageCarts.nn","rodent.nn" )

reg.ss.vars <- c("Abandoned_Buildings.nn", "Abandoned_Cars.nn", "Graffiti.nn","Liquor_Retail.nn", "Street_Lights_Out.nn", "Sanitation.nn","loopDistance","pothole.nn","garbageCarts.nn","rodent.nn", "abandoned.isSig", "abandoned.isSig.dist")

## RUN k-fold REGRESSIONS
reg.ss.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",                           
  dependentVariable = "countNar",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countNar, Prediction, geometry)

##  run LOGO-CV
reg.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",
  dependentVariable = "countNar",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
  dplyr::select(cvID = name, countNar, Prediction, geometry)
    
reg.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countNar",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
  dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countNar, Prediction, geometry)

reg.ss.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countNar",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
  dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countNar, Prediction, geometry)

reg.summary <- 
  rbind(
    mutate(reg.cv,           Error = Prediction - countNar,
           Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Just Risk Factors"),
    
    mutate(reg.ss.cv,        Error = Prediction - countNar,
           Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Spatial Process"),
    
    mutate(reg.spatialCV,    Error = Prediction - countNar,
           Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV: Just Risk Factors"),
    
    mutate(reg.ss.spatialCV, Error = Prediction - countNar,
           Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV: Spatial Process")) %>%
  st_sf()

8 Prediction in race context

Analyzing the mean error in racial context, models tend to under-predict narcotics in neighborhoods where white people are not the major race and over predict in places where white people are the major race. However, model without spatial aggravation has higher errors in prediction.

  reg.summary %>% 
  filter(str_detect(Regression, "LOGO")) %>%
  st_centroid() %>%
  st_join(tracts17) %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  group_by(Regression, raceContext) %>%
  summarize(mean.Error = mean(Error, na.rm = T)) %>%
  spread(raceContext, mean.Error) %>%
  kable(caption = "Mean Error by neighborhood racial context") %>%
  kable_styling("striped", full_width = F)

9 Model Comparison

Here we choose the kernel density model with 1000-foot radius as the baseline model. Compared with Kernel Density Model, the risk prediction model does have higher performance with more accurate prediction in narcotics count in following maps. Also, according to the plot below, risk prediction model have higher accuracy in most cases except in the crime-densest areas.

  cbind(

      dplyr::select(nar18) %>% mutate(countNar = 1), ., sum) %>%

10 Conclusion

This predictive policing model is a useful tool in planning with proper use. Firstly, the model identified the hot spots of narcotics occurrence and matches the 2018 narcotics data points in record. In addition, when it comes to the cross-time narcotics prediction, the risk prediction model does capture narcotics with higher accuracy in most cases compared than traditional kernel density.

However, we need to keep the selection bias in mind. Just as what I mentioned before, the selection bias may exist in dependent variables as well as independent variable in regression model. Police may strengthen the surveillance around the hot spots and find more narcotics. For example, according to the error table under race context, we can clearly see that the model over-predicts risk in White areas and under-predicts in Minority areas. This may unfairly allocate police resource disproportionately in White communities. All of these reasons will relate the data sampling to certain communities or groups. Thus, it will lose generalization across space and lead to false predictions.
